Data Dictionary¶


Dependent Variable

item_cnt_day Numeric Variable Amount of the specific item sold at the specific store on the given date

Independent Variables

**date:** Date-Time series Represents the date the item was sold formated as dd/mm/yyyy
**item_price:** Numeric variable current price of an item
**date_block_num:** Numeric variable a consecutive month number, used for convenience. January 2013 is 0, February 2013 is 1,..., October 2015 is 33
**item_name:** Categorical variable name of the item
**shop_name:** Categorical variable name of the shop

**item_category_name:** Categorical variable name of the Category items belong to.



Descriptive Variables

**Shop ID:** Used to identify a specific shop
**Item ID:** used to identify the item
**item_category_id:** Used to identify the category that the item belongs to

Data Exploration¶

Data questions that we can visualize¶

  1. What are the total sales per store per month
  2. What are the total sales per item per month
  3. What is the growth in total sales per store for each month
  4. What is the highest grossing item (item with the highest sales i.e. price X Items sold) per store per month
  5. What is the average sales per day of week and what is the std of sales per day(Monday-Sunday)
  6. What is the distribution of item prices
  7. What month has the most gross sales
  8. What day has the most gross sales
  9. What week has the gross most sales
  10. What is the Most expense/ lest expensive item

Question 1: What are the total sales per store per month¶

To answer this we must first group our data by month & store

We can do this using the groupby function in pandas and use the date_block_num column which is a int representation of the months (NOTE: the date_block_num column continue to count past 12 so we do not have to worry about grouping the same month from diffrent years together

Ok lets group the months & shops first and take a look at the data. Before we do this however we need to make a new column for sales so that when we group we can get the sales per store instead of a sum of item ids and item qty sold

In [99]:

In [135]:
def Calc_growth(Sales_list):
    counter=0
    growth_list=[]
    for sales in Sales_list:
        if counter == 0:
            x=sales
            counter+=1
            continue
        growth=(sales/x)-1
        x=sales
        growth_list.append(growth)
        counter+=1
    return(growth_list)
